The survey was divided into the following four sections:
Personal Information: This section required personal details of the students, such as
school name, class, gender, academic grade, and coronavirus zone (red zone, yellow
zone, or green zone), in order to analyze any patterns that might be associated with the
demographics of the respondents.
Academic Stress: This section was further subdivided into four parts to evaluate
academic stress arising from different sources in a student's ecological environment.
This included (a) Stress from family, (b) Stress from peers, (c) Stress from school, and
(d) Overall analysis. Parts (a), (b), and (c) each posed three questions that aimed to
analyze the magnitude of the effect of the given stressor. The first question provided
multiple checkboxes presenting examples of how the stressor may be affecting the
student. These examples were provided based on research conducted by Deb et al.
(2015), Parikh et al. (2019), and the author's personal experiences. An open-ended
answer was included for responses not included in the choices. The second question
posed an ordinal variable investigating how the lockdown has affected the stressor as
compared to pre-lockdown conditions. The third question provided a dichotomous
variable inquiring whether the stressor affected the respondent negatively in terms of
mental health and well-being. The last part, (d) Overall analysis, inquired about other
unmentioned stressors that may affect the respondents and how the overall stress has
changed compared to pre-lockdown conditions.
